## @code-builder

Purpose: Start building against a specific Jira task with full context and reproducibility.

Do NOT use this command for pure planning or research-only questions; use `@cmd-planner` or researcher mode instead, then hand off to `@code-builder` once implementation work is agreed.

### Inputs
- Jira key (required) and short task description
- User prompt/acceptance criteria (if any)

### When invoked
1) Confirm Jira context (Atlassian MCP): fetch the issue (key, title, status, summary, assignee, priority). If missing, ask for the key.
2) Refresh constraints: skim `AGENTS.md`, `.cursor/rules/thesis-core.mdc`, `docs/PROJECT.md`, `docs/DECISIONS.md`, and relevant sections of `docs/PLANNER.md` tied to the task.
3) Define the work:
   - Restate goal + acceptance criteria in 3–7 bullets.
   - List likely files to touch; note tests/metrics needed.
   - Propose branch name `thesis/<JIRA-KEY>-<short-slug>`.
4) Execute plan (code + docs):
   - Keep diffs small; avoid new deps unless justified.
   - Preserve reproducibility: fixed seeds, save configs/metrics when running experiments, never commit `runs/` or data.
   - Add comments only where non-obvious; keep code clear.
5) Validation:
   - Run targeted checks/tests; report results.
   - If behavior changes, update relevant docs (PROJECT/CHANGELOG/notes as needed).
6) Handoff:
   - Summarize changes and remind of checkpoint steps (branch, commit message `<JIRA-KEY>: ...`, push). Do not claim git commands were run.

### Constraints
- Do not fabricate results or metrics; if not measured, say so.
- Ask only essential clarifications; otherwise proceed with best-guess plan.
- No PR creation; follow repo’s no-PR policy.

Related commands:
- `@cmd-planner` for planning/decision-making before implementation.
- `@cmd-git-checkpoint` for preparing a clean commit/push.
